  "title": "Exploration 7, due March 15",
  "body": " Exploration 7, due March 15   Exploration 7, due March 15  Make sure to familiarize yourself with the Exploration Instructions found on the home page.  This exploration contains three separate problems.    Find a matrix  with real entries that has no real eigenvalues . Verify your answer by computing the characteristic polynomial of and explaining why it has no real roots.      For each of the following matrices and linear transformations , do the following:  Find all eigenvalues and a corresponding eigenvector for each eigenvalue without calculation by thinking it out using the linear transformation's geometric interpretation .  Graph each eigenvector and its image under the transformation.  Graph a random non‑eigenvector and its image.  Verify correctness using matrix multiplication.   Confirm your intuition by computing:  all eigenvalues,  algebraic and geometric multiplicities,  a basis for each eigenspace.  You may need to do this step first for any transformation that you cannot visualize.         , is the zero transformation.       , is projection onto line.       , is rotation by . Also, state the values of for which has real eigenvectors.       , is reflect about the line and stretch by a factor of 3.       , hint: try and .       , is a shear.       , is project to the side-wall.       , is rotate by about the -axis.       Pick any two transformations from the list above (except the matrix in ). For each one:   Apply a single row operation to to form a new matrix .  Compute the eigenvalues of . Ensure that at least one eigenvalue of differs from the eigenvalues of (this is not guaranteed).  Compute the corresponding eigenvectors.  Compare: Are the eigenvectors for the same as for ? Are they different?   Finish the sentence:   “When you do a single row operation to a matrix , then the eigenvalues … and the eigenvectors … .”      "
